<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-08-11T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-08-11T06:00:00-05:00" n="593" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d593">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.12/36: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-08-11T19:00:00+08:00">August 11, 1930—7
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 7:38 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>689. Department’s 256, July 31, 6 p.m.<note n="34" xml:id="d593fn34">See
                                last paragraph of telegram of the same date to the Consul General at
                                Shanghai, <ref target="#pg_529">p. 529</ref>.</note> Legation has
                            received from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs copies of quarantine
                            regulations with request that those concerned be instructed to comply
                            with the regulations. A reply is being drafted along the lines of the
                            Department’s telegram under reference. Shanghai reported under date of
                                <pb facs="0630" n="532" xml:id="pg_532"/> August 7, 1 p.m., similar
                            reply made to Director of Quarantine. Shanghai informed.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>